How much is car insurance in Oregon? 

To determine how much car insurance is in Oregon, Bankrate analyzed premium data from Quadrant Information Services. According to our research, the average cost of car insurance in Oregon is $2,121 per year for full coverage and $841 per year for minimum coverage. These are just average figures to be used for comparative purposes; your exact car insurance rate will vary based on personal factors like your age, ZIP code, credit history, claims history, driving record and more. To help give you a clearer image of what your insurance costs may be, Bankrate also included average rates for a variety of Oregon driving profiles.

Key takeaways

  • The average car insurance cost in Oregon is $177 per month for full coverage and $70 per month for minimum coverage.
  • If you have poor credit, car insurance costs change by 78 percent more for full coverage on average.
  • Of the cities, Corvallis has the cheapest car insurance rates in Oregon for full coverage at $1,815 for full coverage.
  • Drivers with one accident on their record pay more for insurance an average of $3,166 for full coverage.

Oregon car insurance rates by city

The city and ZIP code you live in also factor into your Oregon car insurance rates. Insurance carriers often use city-specific variables like population density, crime statistics, claim frequency and cost of living in the ZIP code to determine rates in the area. If you live in an area where its more common to file an insurance claim, you will likely pay more for your coverage. Bankrates take: Broadly, car insurance rates are a calculation of risk: if you pose a higher risk of filing a claim with your insurance provider, it is likely your insurer will charge you more for your policy. That is why men typically pay more for car insurance than women: statistics show that men are more likely to drive dangerously and engage in risky practices, which in turn could lead to an expensive claim.

How to save on car insurance in Oregon

Car insurance rates in Oregon are not overly expensive, on average, but there are ways you may be able to save even more money and earn a lower premium. Here are some suggestions for getting cheap car insurance:

  • Get several quotes: To find the best rate for your coverage preferences, you may want to request multiple car insurance quotes from different carriers. This way, you can evaluate coverage options and pricing to find the right carrier.
  • Improve your credit score: If you have a poor credit score, you may pay a higher car insurance premium. Raising your credit score, even by a few points, can help you get a lower rate.
  • Pay your premium in full: Paying your premium upfront and in full may help you get a cheaper rate, if you can afford the out-of-pocket cost.
  • Take a defensive driver course: Many insurance companies offer a discount to drivers who complete an approved defensive driver or driver safety course.
  • Raise your deductibles: Increasing your comprehensive and collision deductibles can lower your premium. Just make sure you can afford a higher deductible if you need to file a claim.
  • Switch carriers: If you find a different insurance company that can offer you a better deal, you can usually switch carriers during your policy period. Youll want to check if your current insurer has any fees associated with policy cancellation.

Frequently asked questions

  • Theres no single best car insurance company in Oregon since insurance is unique for every driver. To help you identify the best provider for you, consider what you value from an insurance company. For instance, if you have a prior incident on your driving record, you might want a company that offers affordable coverage to high-risk drivers. If you work from home, you might look for a company that offers usage-based insurance or a good telematics discount. Once youve narrowed down providers, you can request several quotes to compare coverage and cost.

  • The cheapest car insurance company in Oregon may be different for everyone, as many personal factors determine the price. Travelers, Geico, Mutual of Enumclaw and Capital are among some of the cheapest car insurance companies in Oregon, based on Bankrates research. You may want to request quotes from several of these providers before you make your decision. Dont forget to factor in multi-car discounts and good student or safe driver discounts, which might reduce your monthly insurance premium.

  • Every state has different car insurance requirements. In Oregon, drivers must carry at least 25/50/20 in personal liability insurance, as well as 25/50 in uninsured motorist insurance and $15,000 in PIP per person. However, insurance professionals generally recommend that drivers purchase higher coverage limits or get a full coverage policy, which provides physical damage protection. Driving without insurance in Oregon is against the law, and the penalties could be steep. Drivers who are caught operating a vehicle without proper insurance may face fines, license suspension and may even need to maintain an SR-22 certificate for up to three years.

  • On average, Oregon drivers pay $177 per month for a full coverage car insurance policy and $70 per month for minimum coverage. However, these are just average rates. Exactly what you pay for your Oregon car insurance policy will change depending on your age, gender, credit history, driving history, vehicle make and model and other factors.

  • Premium
    A premium is the amount the policyholder pays to the insurance company, typically on a monthly, semi-annual or annual basis, to maintain an active insurance policy.
    Full coverage car insurance
    Full coverage car insurance provides physical damage coverage for your own vehicle. It typically includes comprehensive and collision coverage in addition to state-mandated liability coverage.
    Deductible
    A deductible is the amount the policyholder agrees to pay out-of-pocket before the insurance company begins to cover expenses related to a claim.

Other profiles

  • Rates were calculated based on the following insurance credit tiers assigned to our drivers: poor, average, good (base) and excellent. Insurance credit tiers factor in your official credit scores but are not dependent on that variable alone. Four states prohibit or limit the use of credit as a rating factor in determining auto insurance rates: California, Hawaii, Massachusetts and Michigan. 

     

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the following incidents applied: clean record (base), at-fault accident, single speeding ticket, single DUI conviction and lapse in coverage.

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the following differences in mileage: 2K, 5K, 12K (base), 15K and 20K.

  • Unless otherwise stated, rates are for 2023 vehicle models. For new vs used vehicles, we included the following year in our calculations: 2013.

  • Rates were calculated by evaluating our base profile with the ages 18-70 (base: 40 years) applied. Depending on age, drivers may be a renter or homeowner. Age is not a contributing rating factor in Hawaii and Massachusetts due to state regulations. For teen drivers, rates were determined by adding a 16- or 17-year-old teen to their 40-year-old married parents' policy. The rates displayed reflect the total cost of a driver this age added to their parents policy. 

  • The following states do not use gender as a determining factor in calculating premiums: California, Hawaii, Massachusetts, Michigan, North Carolina, Pennsylvania.

  • Rates were evaluated based on the following marital/family status: single (base), married, 40-year-old married man and woman. Marital status is not a rating factor in Hawaii and Massachusetts.
